>

  <!-- ── Watch: Cowork Introduction ──────────────────── -->
  <h2 class="section-heading" id="intro-video" data-jump-label="Cowork Introduction from Claude 101">Watch: Co-work Introduction from Claude 101</h2>
  <p class="section-description">Co-work as "Claude Code for non-developers" — sandbox, computer control, Chat vs. Co-work comparison.</p>

  <VideoEmbed
    title="Claude Co-work: Claude Code for Non-Developers"
    src="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1NXwkzf3jtJn8Fu9GcaQr3obgIutFSCFe/preview"
    duration="~4.5 min"
    presenter="Austin Reece"
    date="Claude 101 Training • Feb 5, 2026"
  />

  <!-- ── Overview ────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 class="section-heading" id="overview" data-jump-label="What is Claude Cowork">Overview</h2>
  <p class="section-description">In the Foundations path, you mastered Claude Chat — the conversational interface for thinking through problems, drafting content, and getting answers. Now it's time to level up.</p>

  <p class="section-description"><strong>Claude Cowork</strong> is where Claude stops just talking and starts <em>doing</em>. It's the bridge between conversation and action — an AI collaborator that can work with your actual files, folders, and data on your computer.</p>

  <div class="key-difference">
    <p><strong>The Key Difference:</strong><br>Claude Chat is for <em>thinking together</em>.<br>Claude Cowork is for <em>working together</em>.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Key Differences ────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 class="section-heading" id="key-differences" data-jump-label="Chat vs Cowork Differences">What Makes Cowork Different?</h2>

  <table class="compare-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Capability</th>
        <th>Claude Chat</th>
        <th>Claude Cowork</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Answer questions</td>
        <td class="check">✓</td>
        <td class="check">✓</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Draft content</td>
        <td class="check">✓</td>
        <td class="check">✓</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Access your files</td>
        <td class="cross">✗</td>
        <td class="check">✓</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Move/organize files</td>
        <td class="cross">✗</td>
        <td class="check">✓</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Read spreadsheets & data</td>
        <td>Limited (upload only)</td>
        <td class="check">✓ Full access</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Create files on your computer</td>
        <td class="cross">✗</td>
        <td class="check">✓</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Execute multi-step workflows</td>
        <td class="cross">✗</td>
        <td class="check">✓</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Work while you describe the outcome</td>
        <td class="cross">✗</td>
        <td class="check">✓</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <CalloutBox type="breakthrough" title="The Mental Model">
    <strong>Claude Chat</strong> = A brilliant colleague you can call anytime to talk through ideas<br>
    <strong>Claude Cowork</strong> = That same colleague sitting at your desk, able to actually do the work with you
  </CalloutBox>

  <!-- ── Async Work ────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 class="section-heading" id="async-work" data-jump-label="Cowork Runs While You Work">Cowork Works While You Do Other Things</h2>
  <p class="section-description">One of Cowork's biggest advantages: it doesn't require constant attention</p>

  <div class="terminal-window">
    <div class="terminal-header">
      <div class="terminal-dot" style="background: #ff5f57;"></div>
      <div class="terminal-dot" style="background: #febc2e;"></div>
      <div class="terminal-dot" style="background: #28c840;"></div>
      <span class="terminal-title">Example Request</span>
    </div>
    <div class="terminal-content">
      <span style="color: #a5d6ff;">You:</span> "Analyze all files in my Q4 Reports folder and create a summary document. Save it to my Desktop when done."
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="section-description" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;"><strong>What Cowork does:</strong></p>
  <ol style="list-style: none; counter-reset: step; padding: 0;">
    <li style="padding: 0.75rem 0; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563; font-size: 0.9375rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #f0f0f0; counter-increment: step;"><span style="position: absolute; left: 0; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: #8b5cf6; color: white; border-radius: 50%; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600;">1</span> Acknowledges the task</li>
    <li style="padding: 0.75rem 0; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563; font-size: 0.9375rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #f0f0f0; counter-increment: step;"><span style="position: absolute; left: 0; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: #8b5cf6; color: white; border-radius: 50%; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600;">2</span> Scans the folder</li>
    <li style="padding: 0.75rem 0; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563; font-size: 0.9375rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #f0f0f0; counter-increment: step;"><span style="position: absolute; left: 0; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: #8b5cf6; color: white; border-radius: 50%; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600;">3</span> Analyzes each file</li>
    <li style="padding: 0.75rem 0; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563; font-size: 0.9375rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #f0f0f0; counter-increment: step;"><span style="position: absolute; left: 0; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: #8b5cf6; color: white; border-radius: 50%; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600;">4</span> Creates summary</li>
    <li style="padding: 0.75rem 0; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563; font-size: 0.9375rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #f0f0f0; counter-increment: step;"><span style="position: absolute; left: 0; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: #8b5cf6; color: white; border-radius: 50%; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600;">5</span> Saves to Desktop</li>
    <li style="padding: 0.75rem 0; padding-left: 2rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563; font-size: 0.9375rem; counter-increment: step;"><span style="position: absolute; left: 0; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: #22c55e; color: white; border-radius: 50%; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Reports completion</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="section-description" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;"><strong>What you can do during this time:</strong></p>
  <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0;">
    <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563; font-size: 0.9375rem;"><span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #22c55e; font-weight: 600;">→</span> Switch to other applications</li>
    <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563; font-size: 0.9375rem;"><span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #22c55e; font-weight: 600;">→</span> Work on different tasks</li>
    <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563; font-size: 0.9375rem;"><span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #22c55e; font-weight: 600;">→</span> Take a break</li>
  </ul>

  <CalloutBox type="limitation" title="Key Difference from Chat">
    This is fundamentally different from Chat, where you're actively conversing throughout. Cowork can execute complex tasks autonomously while you focus elsewhere.
  </CalloutBox>

  <!-- ── When to Use ────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 class="section-heading" id="when-to-use" data-jump-label="When to Use Each Mode">When to Use Cowork vs. Chat</h2>

  <h3 style="font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1a1a1a; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Use Claude Chat when you want to:</h3>
  <ul style="list-style: none; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #8b5cf6;">•</span>Brainstorm or think through a problem
    </li>
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #8b5cf6;">•</span>Draft an email, document, or message
    </li>
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #8b5cf6;">•</span>Get explanations or learn something new
    </li>
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #8b5cf6;">•</span>Have a back-and-forth conversation to refine ideas
    </li>
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #8b5cf6;">•</span>Quick questions and answers
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3 style="font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1a1a1a; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Use Claude Cowork when you want to:</h3>
  <ul style="list-style: none; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #22c55e;">•</span>Work with files already on your computer
    </li>
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #22c55e;">•</span>Organize, rename, or move folders
    </li>
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #22c55e;">•</span>Analyze data in spreadsheets or CSVs
    </li>
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #22c55e;">•</span>Create multiple files as part of a project
    </li>
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #22c55e;">•</span>Execute a multi-step workflow
    </li>
    <li style="padding: 0.375rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; position: relative; color: #4b5563;">
      <span style="position: absolute; left: 0; color: #22c55e;">•</span>Have Claude <em>do</em> something rather than just <em>describe</em> it
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CalloutBox type="limitation" title="Rule of Thumb">
    If you find yourself saying "now take that and..." or "can you actually do this?" — you probably want Cowork.
  </CalloutBox>

  <!-- ── Tips Video ────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 class="section-heading" id="tips-video" data-jump-label="Tips and Automation Workarounds">Watch: Co-work Tips from the Team</h2>
  <p class="section-description">Andy's tips: always refresh + Slack reminder workaround for automations.</p>

  <VideoEmbed
    title="Co-work Updates & Automation Workarounds"
    src="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Wr7Ts45LCtwFcfAXJiv-Z5RitoIwDlbk/preview"
    duration="~2 min"
    presenter="Andy D'Amato + Austin Reece"
    date="Claude 101 Training • Feb 5, 2026"
  />

  <!-- ── Examples ────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 class="section-heading" id="examples" data-jump-label="Real-World Cowork Examples">Cowork in Action: Real Examples</h2>
  <p class="section-description">Let's look at the types of tasks where Cowork shines. These aren't hypotheticals — they're the everyday workflows that make Cowork invaluable.</p>

  <!-- Example 1: Organizing Files -->
  <div class="example-card">
    <h4>Example 1: Organizing Files</h4>
    <p class="example-subtitle">You have a Downloads folder that's become a graveyard of random files. You need to organize it but keep putting it off.</p>

    <div class="example-section">
      <h5>What You'd Say:</h5>
      <div class="terminal-window">
        <div class="terminal-header">
          <div class="terminal-dot red"></div>
          <div class="terminal-dot yellow"></div>
          <div class="terminal-dot green"></div>
          <span class="terminal-title">prompt</span>
        </div>
        <div class="terminal-content">I need help organizing my Downloads folder. Can you:
1. Look at what's in there
2. Suggest a folder structure based on file types
3. Show me the plan before moving anything
4. Then organize the files once I approve</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="example-section">
      <h5>What Cowork Does:</h5>
      <div class="cowork-response">
        <ul>
          <li>Scans your Downloads folder</li>
          <li>Identifies file types (PDFs, images, spreadsheets, documents, etc.)</li>
          <li>Proposes a structure like: /Documents, /Images, /Spreadsheets, /Installers, /Archive</li>
          <li>Waits for your approval</li>
          <li>Moves files into the new structure</li>
          <li>Reports what was moved where</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-point">
      <p><strong>Key Point:</strong> Notice the approval step. Cowork plans before acting — you stay in control.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 2: Analyzing Data -->
  <div class="example-card">
    <h4>Example 2: Analyzing Data</h4>
    <p class="example-subtitle">You have a CSV export from Salesforce with 6 months of opportunity data. You need to understand win rates by segment.</p>

    <div class="example-section">
      <h5>What You'd Say:</h5>
      <div class="terminal-window">
        <div class="terminal-header">
          <div class="terminal-dot red"></div>
          <div class="terminal-dot yellow"></div>
          <div class="terminal-dot green"></div>
          <span class="terminal-title">prompt</span>
        </div>
        <div class="terminal-content">I have a Salesforce export at /Users/me/Documents/Q3-Q4-opps.csv

Can you analyze this and tell me:
- Win rate by customer segment
- Average deal size by segment
- How win rates have trended month over month
- Any segments where we're losing more than winning

Show me the analysis and create a summary I could share with leadership.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="example-section">
      <h5>What Cowork Does:</h5>
      <div class="cowork-response">
        <ul>
          <li>Reads the CSV file directly</li>
          <li>Processes the data (no upload needed — it accesses your file system)</li>
          <li>Calculates the metrics you requested</li>
          <li>Creates visualizations if helpful</li>
          <li>Generates a shareable summary document</li>
          <li>Saves the summary to your specified location</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-point">
      <p><strong>Key Point:</strong> Cowork works with files <em>in place</em>. No uploading, no copy-pasting, no "here's the data" back and forth.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 3: Multi-File Project Setup -->
  <div class="example-card">
    <h4>Example 3: Multi-File Project Setup</h4>
    <p class="example-subtitle">You're starting a new enablement project and need to set up the folder structure with template files.</p>

    <div class="example-section">
      <h5>What You'd Say:</h5>
      <div class="terminal-window">
        <div class="terminal-header">
          <div class="terminal-dot red"></div>
          <div class="terminal-dot yellow"></div>
          <div class="terminal-dot green"></div>
          <span class="terminal-title">prompt</span>
        </div>
        <div class="terminal-content">I'm starting a new project called "Q1 SKO Prep"

Can you create a project folder structure at /Users/me/Projects/Q1-SKO-Prep with:
- A planning folder with a blank project brief template
- A content folder with subfolders for presentations, handouts, and videos
- A logistics folder for venue, catering, and travel
- A README file explaining the folder structure

Use our standard project brief template if you know it, otherwise create a basic one.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="example-section">
      <h5>What Cowork Does:</h5>
      <div class="cowork-response">
        <ul>
          <li>Creates the folder structure</li>
          <li>Generates template files</li>
          <li>Writes the README</li>
          <li>Reports back what was created</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-point">
      <p><strong>Key Point:</strong> Cowork can create entire project scaffolds in seconds — work that would take you 15+ minutes of clicking and typing.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 4: Batch File Operations -->
  <div class="example-card">
    <h4>Example 4: Batch File Operations</h4>
    <p class="example-subtitle">You have 47 screenshots from a product demo that need to be renamed from "Screenshot 2024-01-15 at 3.42.17 PM.png" to something useful.</p>

    <div class="example-section">
      <h5>What You'd Say:</h5>
      <div class="terminal-window">
        <div class="terminal-header">
          <div class="terminal-dot red"></div>
          <div class="terminal-dot yellow"></div>
          <div class="terminal-dot green"></div>
          <span class="terminal-title">prompt</span>
        </div>
        <div class="terminal-content">I have a folder of demo screenshots at /Users/me/Desktop/Demo-Screenshots

Can you:
1. Look at each image
2. Rename them based on what's shown in the screenshot
3. Add a sequence number prefix so they stay in order
4. Show me the proposed renames before executing</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="example-section">
      <h5>What Cowork Does:</h5>
      <div class="cowork-response">
        <ul>
          <li>Opens each image</li>
          <li>Analyzes the content (sees "login screen", "dashboard", "settings page", etc.)</li>
          <li>Proposes renames like: 01-login-screen.png, 02-dashboard-overview.png, 03-customer-profile.png</li>
          <li>Shows you the plan</li>
          <li>Executes after approval</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-point">
      <p><strong>Key Point:</strong> Cowork can <em>see</em> images and make intelligent decisions based on content — not just metadata.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

